## The fixed throttle

```js
function throttle(fn, ms) {
  let last = 0, timer = null, lastArgs = null;
  return (...a) => {
    const now = Date.now();
    const remaining = ms - (now - last);
    if (remaining <= 0) {                 // window open → fire now (leading edge)
      if (timer) { clearTimeout(timer); timer = null; }
      last = now;
      fn(...a);
    } else {                              // inside cooldown → remember for the trailing edge
      lastArgs = a;
      if (!timer) {
        timer = setTimeout(() => {
          last = Date.now();
          timer = null;
          fn(...lastArgs);
          lastArgs = null;
        }, remaining);
      }
    }
  };
}
```

## Why the original failed

Your version only had a leading edge: `if (now - last >= ms) fn(...)`. Every call that arrives *during* the cooldown window just falls off the end of the arrow function and is discarded — there's no timer to replay the last one. So in a burst (scroll, resize, keypress), the final event never fires, which is usually the one you care about.

